Kristin,

I think so. I first came to AS3 in the late 90s... I forget the exact
year. Stayed quit for a couple of years and then decided that I would
have &quot;just one&quot;. We all know what that means, don't we? Well, seven
years later, I dragged my butt back to AS3. I now have almost three
months without a cigarette.

My thinking during the previous seven years when I was smoking was very
strange. I quickly fell back into thinking that it would be impossible
for me to quit! I felt like I would be a smoker my whole life. Kristin,
you may have forgotten just like I did that it IS possible to quit. We
CAN be non-smokers. You too can become a non-smoker like you were
before. You had a year smober, remember??? You CAN quit again. The
monster we believe is waiting for us when we quit is in reality only a
pesky mosquito that bothers us less and less the further away we get
from our last cigarette.

Look, I'm NOT saying that quitting is a breeze. It isn't. But have a
plan. I'm sure you'll get PLENTY of suggestions in this group for tools
you can use; nicotine gum, Chantix, Wellbutrin, cold turkey are some of
the various ways we AS3'ers have successfully quit smoking. You choose
the one that you think will work for you.

Above all, read the posts here and post your own messages when you need
to. We are a very supportive group of people. You've already taken one
huge step by posting this message so follow through with it.

Good luck and I look forward to seeing your next post.  :)

ConcordPhil
I have not smoked in 2M 3W 6D 5h 34m. That's 88 days! I have not used
any nicotine at all since 9/03/2007.
