i suspect the truth is that you never got over your addiction in the first
place. a lot of people make the mistake of thinking that after a relatively
short period of time they have overcome their addiction whereas in reality
it tends to hang around for a lot longer, often in subtle forms.

after a year of not smoking you thought that you needed to smoke in order to
deal with your relationship sadness. you didn't need to smoke and smoking
wasn't going to help you at all but for some reason you decided that smoking
was a viable solution and you need to understand why you did that. you are
now saying that you need to smoke to deal with work stress but you don't so
you need to think about that as well.

you are addicted to smoking and you need to understand that as an 'addict'
you are capable of coming up with no end of 'reasons' why you need/want to
smoke and that they are all lies.  take a good look at as3's junkie
thinking.

smoking is not going to do anything that's beneficial for you. in fact the
opposite is true and smoking is going to do nothing but harm you and stop
you from doing things and living your life to the full.  you're missing out
on the training and friends that you used to work out with but that's only
the beginning and  not being able to take part in a triathlon is a shame but
not being able to walk up a flight of stairs without getting dizzy and
feeling that your lungs are collapsing is a tragedy and that's what you have
to 'look forward' to if you keep smoking (and all the other shitty stuff
that smoking can do to your body)!

if you're going to stop smoking you have to understand that smoking doesn't
help anything! smoking will only ever make things worse because whatever
your problems are, smoking will just add another problem to them.

decide what you want for yourself. decide what's important to you. make the
choice and commit yourself to it.

my advice is.......stop smoking right now and get back into training.

but the question is...........what do you want?

one last thing, putting off the decision to stop smoking is the same as
deciding to continue.

best wishes

richard

