Nah.. you started smoking because you lit up that one cigarette. And
did it help you at all to cope? I doubt it. All it got you were
additional problems. Stinky clothes, burn holes, rollercoated of need
and feed nicotine, not working out anymore, lost social contacts.. You
would've gotten through the sadness whithout smoking as well.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Now it is October and I'm still smoking and no longer
&gt; working out.  I'm missing out on the training and the friends that
&gt; used to work out with.  I keep trying to quit. but the stress of
&gt; work gets me by 4pm.
">

It's the withdrawal that gets you at 4 MP. You been without a smoke
long enough for the feeding cues to get overwhelming. You get nervous,
jittery, impatient, and all you can think of is that cigarette you can
smoke when work is done. Try and remember your 4pm's at work, while
you were smober that year. Do you recall them as being so stressful
you just HAD to smoke?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I'm now feeling like I'm addicted again.
&gt; Any inspiration for me?
">

This may sound hard but ex-addict is a word that is non-existent. Once
you quit, the only thing that keeps you from smoking is never take the
next one again. Once you do, you fall back hostage to your addiction.
You will forever be on probation. 1 is either all or go through
withdrawal again. So far, you are opting for all, instead of
withdrawal. However, all is forever, withdrawal is temporary.

